{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16634"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16634"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.24,0.42,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67792"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16634"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53257"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5203"},{"type":"tags","id":"5221"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22455"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67792"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMethadone is commonly used in opioid replacement therapy programs for the treatment of opioid dependence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacological properties of methadone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Short-acting full agonist at mu-opioid receptors","Partial agonist at mu-opioid receptors","Full agonist at mu-opioid receptors with long half-life","Mixed agonist-antagonist at mu-opioid receptors","Antagonist at mu-opioid receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMethadone is a \u003Cstrong\u003Efull agonist at mu-opioid receptors with long half-life\u003C/strong\u003E. It is predominantly utilised as a form of opioid replacement therapy however is infrequently used in chronic pain. Its long duration of action (24-36 hours) makes it suitable for once-daily dosing in opioid replacement therapy. It also has NMDA receptor antagonist properties which may help prevent the development of opioid tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort-acting full agonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like morphine, whereas methadone has a characteristically long duration of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial agonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes buprenorphine, which has a ceiling effect on respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed agonist-antagonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like pentazocine, which can precipitate withdrawal in opioid-dependent patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like naloxone and naltrexone, which block rather than activate opioid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe long half-life of methadone helps prevent the peaks and troughs in blood levels seen with shorter-acting opioids, reducing withdrawal symptoms and cravings in patients with opioid dependence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Methadone is a long-acting synthetic opioid that acts as a full mu-opioid receptor agonist.","Methadone has a long half-life of 24-36 hours, allowing once-daily dosing for opioid replacement therapy.","Methadone also acts as an N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor antagonist, which may help reduce opioid tolerance."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53257"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16634"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53257"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T07:35:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T07:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67792"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (